The 90 DPOs that <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>you</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> want on this pet are easily achievable with only conflag-like nukes. <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub140.ezboard.com/bgraffeswizardcompilation.showUserPublicProfile?gid=natanmagus>Natan Magus</A> at: 5/20/03 4:10:01 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub140.ezboard.com/bgraffeswizardcompilation.showUserPublicProfile?gid=balanzsonofanz>Balanz son of Anz</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Channeler</span><br>  Posts: 219<br> <font color=#ffffff>(5/20/03 4:21 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> A mage responds</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>I said many mages want it to go live. Where did I get that impression? From a mage site.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->I will tell you a story.<br>
<br>
Once upon a time, a long time ago, mages had four elementals they depended on: earth, air, water and <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><span style="text-decoration:underline">fire</span><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END-->.  For many mages, fire was their <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><span style="text-decoration:underline">favorite</span><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> elemental, because it fought well and had a powerful damage tool.  When the mage was alone, he often chose the fire elemental as his boon companion.<br>
<br>
Then <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Kunark</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> came along.  The level cap was raised from 50 to 60, and mages got new pets.  Three of the new elementals, earth, air, and water became both more powerful and more specialized, but one of the elementals, fire, became both much weaker and more specialized, so that it was practically no longer useful.<br>
<br>
Mages were sad.  They had lost a friend, and had it replaced with an imposter.  The mages were angry.  They complained and petitioned and proposed many solutions for making their friend useful again so that they might fight beside them once more.  But through many years and many expansions, and the gods were either silent or responded cryptically that all was <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>&quot;working as intended.&quot;</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
The mages then went about their business, most of them focussed on other things.  Since the gods did not listen, and were in the habit of not listening, nor responding, the mages expected little.<br>
<br>
Then one day, there was a surprise.<br>
<br>
In the forum where the mages congregated one mage announced unexpected news.  On <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Test</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, which is where the gods tormented mortals with possibilities, a change was proposed whereby the mage's old friend, the fire elemental, would be granted great powers.  By all reports, these new fire elementals, rather than sucking badly as all had for many years, were actually decent and might actually rule.  Even more spectacularly, they cast a really good looking spell.<br>
<br>
The mages were so happy that they might fight alongside their old friend again after many years that they let out many cheers.  Their cries and exhortations were heard wide and far.<br>
<br>
Sadly, the mages were so enraptured with the possibility of a decent and worthwhile fire elemental that most did not reason through all the consequences of this.  Indeed, this is why the gods deliberately torment mortals, or <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Test</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> them, so the mortals may do the gods' dirty work of foreseeing consequences.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Bottom line:</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
Anyone who did not expect mages to express joy at the possible worthwhile upgrade to post-50 fire elementals ignores the emotional context of the proposed fix for mages.  Anyone who mistakes the initial joyous reaction of mages to improving their fire pet for a reasoned and responsible reaction is ignoring human nature.<br>
<br>
Ask <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><span style="text-decoration:underline">any</span><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> mage you might see, in game or in forum, if they would be happy with post-50 fire elementals that did not suck, that indeed would be useful, and you will get a resounding <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><span style="text-decoration:underline">yes</span><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END-->.<br>
<br>
Anyone who seeks to damn magicians for their honest joy is simply out to damn magicians.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Razamatazz Pizzazz</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
